{"title_page": "Latin America and the Caribbean", "text_new": "The term '''Latin America and the Caribbean''' ('''LAC''')<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/new/en/unesco/worldwide/latin-america-and-the-caribbean/ Latin America and the Caribbean]</ref> is an [[English language|English-language]] [[acronym]] referring to the [[Caribbean]] and [[Latin America]] region. The term LAC covers an extensive region, extending from the [[Bahamas]] and [[Mexico]] to [[Argentina]] and [[Chile]]. The region consists over 670,230,000 people {{as of|2016|lc=y}}, and spanned for {{convert|21,951,000|km2|sqmi}}.\n\n== List of countries and territories by subregion ==\n=== Central America ===\n{{Main|Central America}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=85%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Belize}}\n* {{flag|Costa Rica}}\n* {{flag|El Salvador}}\n* {{flag|Guatemala}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Honduras}}\n* {{flag|Mexico}}<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Nicaragua}}\n* {{flag|Panama}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> The [[United Nations geoscheme|UN]] includes [[Mexico]] in [[Central America]]<ref>[https://unstats.un.org/unsd/methodology/m49/ UNSD Methodology \u2013 Standard country or area codes for statistical use (M49)]</ref>.\n\n=== South America ===\n{{Main|South America}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Argentina}}\n* {{flag|Bolivia}}\n* {{flag|Bouvet Island}} ([[Norway]])\n* {{flag|Brazil}}\n* {{flag|Chile}}\n* {{flag|Colombia}}\n* {{flag|Ecuador}} (including the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]])\n* {{flag|Falkland Islands|name=Falkland Islands / Islas Malvinas}}<sup>*</sup> ([[United Kingdom]])\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|French Guiana}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Guyana}}\n* {{flag|Paraguay}}\n* {{flag|Peru}}\n* {{flag|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands}}<sup>*</sup> ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Suriname}}\n* {{flag|Uruguay}}\n* {{flag|Venezuela}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> [[Territorial dispute|Disputed territories]] administered by the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n=== West Indies ===\n{{Main|West Indies}}\n\n==== Caribbean ====\n{{Main|Caribbean}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Anguilla}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Antigua and Barbuda}}\n* {{flag|Aruba}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bajo Nuevo Bank]]<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Barbados}}\n* {{flag|Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba}} ([[Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|British Virgin Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Cayman Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Cuba}}\n* {{flag|Cura\u00e7ao}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|Dominica}}\n* {{flag|Dominican Republic}}\n* {{flag|Federal Dependencies of Venezuela}}\n* {{flag|Grenada}}\n* {{flag|Guadeloupe}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Haiti}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Jamaica}}\n* {{flag|Martinique}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Montserrat}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Navassa Island}} ([[United States]])\n* {{flag|Nueva Esparta}} ([[Venezuela]])\n* {{flag|Puerto Rico}} ([[United States]])\n* {{flag|Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n* {{flag|Saint Lucia}}\n* {{flag|Collectivity of Saint Martin|name=Saint Martin}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n* {{flag|Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina|name=San Andr\u00e9s and Providencia}} ([[Colombia]])\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Serranilla Bank]]<sup>*</sup>\n* {{flag|Sint Maarten}} ([[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]])\n* {{flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n* {{flag|United States Virgin Islands}} ([[United States]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n<sup>*</sup> [[Territorial dispute|Disputed territories]] administered by [[Colombia]].\n\n==== Lucayan Archipelago ====\n{{Main|Lucayan Archipelago}}\n\n{{col-begin|width=200%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Bahamas}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Turks and Caicos Islands}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Somewhat are included===\n{{col-begin|width=115%}}\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Bermuda}} ([[United Kingdom]])\n* {{flag|Clipperton Island}} ([[France]])\n* {{flag|Easter Island}} ([[Chile]])\n{{col-break}}\n* {{flag|Quebec}} ([[Canada]])\n* {{flag|Saint Pierre and Miquelon}} ([[France]])\n* {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Isla Salas y G\u00f3mez|Salas y G\u00f3mez Island]] ([[Chile]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Economy==\nIt is estimated to attribute for over 400 billion dollars that form the core for [[economic stability]], however, few countries, notably [[Venezuela]], are parts of the [[OPEC]].\n\n==Instability==\nThe region has a unique history and varied between stability to instability, included various deadly conflicts, though its level remains conflicted. The two deadliest conflicts in the region are [[Colombian conflict]] and [[Mexican Drug War]]; and more recently, the [[crisis in Venezuela]]. Some other bloody conflicts also include the [[Internal conflict in Peru]] and gang wars in Brazil, Honduras and Argentina. Other conflicts include [[Mapuche conflict]] in Chile and Argentina; and [[Insurgency in Paraguay]]. These conflicts, however, have received lesser attentions from international media, and varied by time, with Colombia in headline in 1990s, Mexico in the 2000s and currently, Venezuela.\n\n==Culture==\n===Religion===\nMost countries are dominated by [[Christianity]], the largest being [[Roman Catholic]]. Smaller groups include [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodoxy]] and [[Protestantism]].\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|Music of Latin America|List of Caribbean music genres}}\n\nThe region is extremely popular for its own distinct [[music]] which can't be found somewhere in the world. Began since the conquest of Spain, France, Britain, the Netherlands and Portugal in 15th century, due to the greater diversification including indigenous, Asian, African and European population merged together, it expanded popularity of their music, dated from 1950s and rampant globalization, music from the region has become widely noticed, and has been nominated for several music awards.<ref>[https://fas.calendar.utoronto.ca/course/mus305h1 MUS305H1: Latin American and Caribbean Music]</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nThe region is very rich at sporting activites, especially in [[association football]], which have some of the world's strongest football teams like [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], etc; though [[baseball]], [[tennis]], [[cycling]], [[volleyball]], [[rugby union]], [[basketball]], [[hockey]], [[cricket]], also gain recent popularity.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Americas (terminology)]]\n* [[Caribbean]]\n* [[Central America]]\n* [[Community of Latin American and Caribbean States]] (CELAC)\n* [[Latin America]]\n* [[Latin American and Caribbean Group]]\n* [[Latin Americans]]\n* [[North America]]\n* [[Northern America]]\n* [[South America]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme for the Americas]]\n* [[United Nations Statistics Division]] (UNSD)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://unstats.un.org/unsd/methodology/m49/ UN Statistics Division \u2013 Standard country or area codes for statistical use (M49)]\n\n{{Caribbean topic}}\n{{Caribbean topics}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lac}}\n\n[[Category:Economic country classifications]]\n[[Category:Latin America]]\n[[Category:Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Acronyms]]\n", "text_old": "The term '''Latin America and the Caribbean''' ('''LAC''')<ref>[http://www.unesco.org/new/en/unesco/worldwide/latin-america-and-the-caribbean/ Latin America and the Caribbean]</ref> is an [[English language|English-language]] [[acronym]] referring to the [[Caribbean]] and [[Latin America]] region. The term LAC covers an extensive region, extending from [[Bahamas]] and [[Mexico]] to [[Argentina]] and [[Chile]]. The region consists over 670,230,000 people {{as of|2016|lc=y}}, and spanned for {{convert|21,951,000|km2|sqmi}}.\n\n== List of countries and territories by subregion ==\n=== Central America =